After reading [this article](https://www.tabsoverspaces.com/233659-do-not-await-what-does-not-need-to-be-awaited) on excessive `await` usage I decided to remove awaiting where possible. This lead to an issue with my data services because of two reasons:

1. All methods that retrieve collection return `Task&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt;` by convention
2. EF does not provide `ToEnumerableAsync`.

Now when I remove `await` the compiler no longer unfolds `Task` objects and I am left with compilation error which says that `Task&lt;List&lt;T&gt;&gt;` cannot be converted to `Task&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt;`.

So I set out to create my own `ToEnumerableAsnyc`. The &quot;PoC&quot; version looked like this:
```c#
public static IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; ToEnumerableAsync&lt;T&gt;(this IQueryable&lt;T&gt; source)
    =&gt; (await source.ToListAsync()).AsEnumerable();
```
However this only wraps the extra `await` and does not remove it, i.e. there is still my `await` and the one used internally from `ToListAsync`. To my understanding from the above linked article this generates unnecessary overhead. It&#39;s not signifficant, but is an overhead none the less. Please correct me if I am wrong :)

So I set out to find how Microsoft devs went about to implement `ToListAsync` in **ASP.NET Core 2.2** and I managed to create my own implementation of `ToEnumerableAsync`, which does not use `await` based on their solution. That&#39;s how it looks:

```c#
public static Task&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; ToEnumerableAsync&lt;T&gt;(this IQueryable&lt;T&gt; queryable)
{
    var asyncEnum = AsAsyncEnumerable(queryable);
    var list = new List&lt;T&gt;();

    return asyncEnum.Aggregate(
        (IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;)list,
        (list, x) =&gt;
        {
            ((List&lt;T&gt;)list).Add(x);
            return list;
        });
}

private static IAsyncEnumerable&lt;T&gt; AsAsyncEnumerable&lt;T&gt;(this IQueryable&lt;T&gt; queryable)
{
    if (queryable is IAsyncEnumerable&lt;T&gt; asyncEnumerable)
    {
        return asyncEnumerable;
    }

    throw new InvalidOperationException(
        $&quot;Cannot cast \&quot;IQueryable\&quot; to \&quot;IAsyncEnumerable\&quot;. Type: \&quot;{typeof(T).FullName}\&quot;&quot;);
}
```

And finally to my question: What can go wrong with the cast of `IQueryable&lt;T&gt;` to `IAsyncEnumerable&lt;T&gt;` that the devs put explicit `InvalidOperationExeption`? How and why can an `IQueryable&lt;T&gt;` fail to cast to `IAsyncEnumerable&lt;T&gt;`?

Original EF file: [QueriableExtensions.cs](https://github.com/aspnet/EntityFrameworkCore/blob/release/2.2/src/EFCore/Extensions/Internal/QueryableExtensions.cs).

